1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,640
 Welcome to chapter two, Types, Operators, and Expressions.

2
00:00:04,640 --> 00:00:06,880
 So again, I'm not going to tell you everything.

3
00:00:06,880 --> 00:00:08,200
 The book, I want you to read the book.

4
00:00:08,200 --> 00:00:09,280
 The book does a great job.

5
00:00:09,280 --> 00:00:10,600
 I'm just gonna call your attention

6
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:13,200
 to some things that might seem a little bit weird

7
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:15,600
 if you're coming from a language like Python

8
00:00:15,600 --> 00:00:20,280
 or JavaScript or even PHP where things are objects

9
00:00:20,280 --> 00:00:21,560
 and you don't even notice it.

10
00:00:21,560 --> 00:00:23,560
 You've been using objects your whole career

11
00:00:23,560 --> 00:00:25,320
 and you didn't even realize it.

12
00:00:25,320 --> 00:00:28,360
 So we're gonna talk about data types and storage allocation.

13
00:00:28,360 --> 00:00:30,240
 One of the things that you just got,

14
00:00:30,240 --> 00:00:33,040
 part of what I love about teaching this historical view on C

15
00:00:33,040 --> 00:00:36,520
 is that we have to talk about storage allocation.

16
00:00:36,520 --> 00:00:39,200
 Float and double worked out pretty well,

17
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:41,400
 partly because in the early days of C,

18
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:43,480
 they did them all in software, so they just made them easy

19
00:00:43,480 --> 00:00:45,240
 and they made them work well.

20
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:47,520
 They weren't expected to be fast.

21
00:00:47,520 --> 00:00:49,920
 The things that they wanted to be super fast

22
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:53,720
 were like the integer and byte data, character data.

23
00:00:53,720 --> 00:00:56,760
 Type conversion, and then there's a story

24
00:00:56,760 --> 00:00:59,080
 that connects integer division in Python 2

25
00:00:59,080 --> 00:01:02,360
 and all that pain of Python 3 and how division changed

26
00:01:02,360 --> 00:01:05,160
 and why it was the way it was and how that worked.

27
00:01:05,160 --> 00:01:06,880
 And again, it has to do with performance

28
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:09,080
 and simple decisions that got made, sadly.

29
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:12,880
 Bitwise logical operations, we'll talk about them.

30
00:01:12,880 --> 00:01:15,000
 You're probably not going to use them,

31
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:17,520
 but it's really important in a historical context

32
00:01:17,520 --> 00:01:20,480
 to understand why they were so thorough.

33
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:23,040
 And it really had to do with the fact that

34
00:01:23,040 --> 00:01:27,080
 because of word oriented computers switching to character

35
00:01:27,080 --> 00:01:29,240
 oriented computers, all of us programmers

36
00:01:29,240 --> 00:01:31,960
 were thinking in words and if we didn't see shifting

37
00:01:31,960 --> 00:01:34,120
 and masking and bitwise stuff, we'd be like,

38
00:01:34,120 --> 00:01:37,080
 I can't program in this thing 'cause a lot of our work

39
00:01:37,080 --> 00:01:39,880
 in those word oriented computers was masking and shifting.

40
00:01:39,880 --> 00:01:42,600
 And so it's like we had to have it.

41
00:01:42,600 --> 00:01:46,480
 We didn't use it as much as we could have thought.

42
00:01:46,480 --> 00:01:49,160
 So let's start with division.

43
00:01:51,120 --> 00:01:53,680
 (sighs)

44
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:57,400
 In the good old days, we were not worried too much

45
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:01,440
 about doing division and if you were doing division

46
00:02:01,440 --> 00:02:04,040
 and you cared about the division,

47
00:02:04,040 --> 00:02:05,520
 you were probably doing it in floating point

48
00:02:05,520 --> 00:02:07,320
 because you were doing scientific computing

49
00:02:07,320 --> 00:02:09,080
 and you did that on supercomputers.

50
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:11,280
 You didn't do that on general purpose computers.

51
00:02:11,280 --> 00:02:13,640
 Unixer's really designed for general purpose computers

52
00:02:13,640 --> 00:02:17,760
 and in general purpose computers, you thought to yourself,

53
00:02:17,760 --> 00:02:19,840
 why is division that important?

54
00:02:19,840 --> 00:02:21,960
 And I'm sure they made some decision somewhere.

55
00:02:21,960 --> 00:02:23,680
 I do not know why.

56
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:25,400
 It probably had to do with one of the computers

57
00:02:25,400 --> 00:02:29,240
 they were working with had truncating division in hardware

58
00:02:29,240 --> 00:02:32,080
 and non-truncating division in software.

59
00:02:32,080 --> 00:02:34,640
 I don't know, or rounding division or whatever.

60
00:02:34,640 --> 00:02:36,960
 A lot of those computers didn't even have

61
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:38,880
 fast floating point, so some of the computers

62
00:02:38,880 --> 00:02:41,840
 they were working on did all the floating point in software

63
00:02:41,840 --> 00:02:44,800
 and maybe they even did integer division in software

64
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:47,960
 with loops and stuff, but we don't know.

65
00:02:47,960 --> 00:02:52,600
 I don't exactly know, but they made this decision

66
00:02:52,600 --> 00:02:56,560
 to do integer division truncating.

67
00:02:56,560 --> 00:02:59,040
 And this was one of the biggest things

68
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:00,920
 of going from Python 2 to Python 3

69
00:03:00,920 --> 00:03:03,240
 that was the most painful.

70
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:08,040
 So Python 2 was over 25 years old

71
00:03:08,040 --> 00:03:11,720
 and it wasn't that long after C that Python 2 was written.

72
00:03:11,720 --> 00:03:14,160
 Python 2 was written in C.

73
00:03:14,160 --> 00:03:18,840
 And Python 2 to Python 3 transition was a big deal.

74
00:03:18,840 --> 00:03:22,240
 It took a long time, it took 12 years to get there.

75
00:03:22,240 --> 00:03:25,080
 But Python 2 was like the greatest thing ever

76
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:27,680
 except for a few things.

77
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:29,640
 Because Python 2 was so related to C,

78
00:03:29,640 --> 00:03:33,440
 the strings in Python 2 natively were ASCII, not Unicode,

79
00:03:33,440 --> 00:03:37,120
 which meant it couldn't even do like Spanish characters,

80
00:03:37,120 --> 00:03:40,040
 let alone Asian characters.

81
00:03:40,040 --> 00:03:41,520
 Print was part of the language

82
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:44,080
 and the programmers got a lot of help.

83
00:03:44,080 --> 00:03:46,160
 Like they got an automated code converter

84
00:03:46,160 --> 00:03:49,280
 and syntax checkers and they did all kinds of things

85
00:03:49,280 --> 00:03:51,000
 where they would take certain libraries

86
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,600
 like the print function and they would put it in Python 3

87
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:55,480
 and then we backported to Python 2.

88
00:03:55,480 --> 00:03:57,800
 So you could like switch from using the print statement

89
00:03:57,800 --> 00:03:58,840
 to the print function.

90
00:03:58,840 --> 00:04:01,400
 And there were lots of things that made this transition

91
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:02,960
 as easy as possible.

92
00:04:02,960 --> 00:04:07,120
 The one thing that they really never could crack

93
00:04:07,120 --> 00:04:10,040
 and we just had to bite the bullet and get used to it

94
00:04:10,040 --> 00:04:15,040
 was Python 2 returns integer and the division is truncated.

95
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:20,520
 So if you do three divided by four is zero in Python 2.

96
00:04:20,520 --> 00:04:25,840
 And in Python 3, integer three divided by integer four

97
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:28,360
 becomes a floating point 0.75

98
00:04:28,360 --> 00:04:31,640
 because that's what calculators do.

99
00:04:31,640 --> 00:04:33,720
 And the Python 2 division truncated

100
00:04:33,720 --> 00:04:37,800
 because it didn't seem like it mattered much back in the 80s

101
00:04:37,800 --> 00:04:40,080
 and C integer division truncated.

102
00:04:40,080 --> 00:04:41,240
 (coughs)

103
00:04:41,240 --> 00:04:43,880
 So three quarters in C was zero

104
00:04:43,880 --> 00:04:46,640
 and three quarters, integer three quarters was zero in C

105
00:04:46,640 --> 00:04:48,320
 and so it was in Python.

106
00:04:48,320 --> 00:04:50,480
 And 20 plus years later,

107
00:04:50,480 --> 00:04:53,520
 that was the one thing we couldn't auto convert

108
00:04:53,520 --> 00:04:56,880
 and Python 3 does it the way Python does.

109
00:04:56,880 --> 00:05:00,520
 So it's less of a problem in C

110
00:05:00,520 --> 00:05:02,760
 because C is actually a strongly typed language

111
00:05:02,760 --> 00:05:06,640
 which means if I wanted to say three over four,

112
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:08,920
 I knew whether it was integers or floats

113
00:05:08,920 --> 00:05:10,200
 and I could force that.

114
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:15,640
 And so, but in Python you just, what's the variable?

115
00:05:15,640 --> 00:05:17,640
 And so it imputes the variable type

116
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:20,120
 from the result of that expression.

117
00:05:20,120 --> 00:05:23,000
 Where C has got to declare X as a float

118
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:23,840
 or a double or an int.

119
00:05:23,840 --> 00:05:25,720
 So when a C programmer writes a division,

120
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:27,920
 they need to know, they know already

121
00:05:27,920 --> 00:05:29,600
 that they have to cast the values

122
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:30,760
 or use float constants

123
00:05:30,760 --> 00:05:33,160
 to trigger type conversion and expressions.

124
00:05:33,160 --> 00:05:34,720
 So as you're looking through the chapters

125
00:05:34,720 --> 00:05:37,480
 seeing these type conversions and casting,

126
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:40,520
 that's the kind of problem that was solved.

127
00:05:40,520 --> 00:05:42,640
 But then Python simplified it

128
00:05:42,640 --> 00:05:47,120
 and then made it really kind of yucky

129
00:05:47,120 --> 00:05:48,160
 and then they had to fix it.

130
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:49,760
 It's better in Python 3

131
00:05:49,760 --> 00:05:52,360
 and most of you have just learned Python 3

132
00:05:52,360 --> 00:05:54,240
 so consider yourself lucky.

133
00:05:54,240 --> 00:05:57,280
 So another thing they talk about a lot

134
00:05:57,280 --> 00:05:59,360
 and it has to do with as we start thinking

135
00:05:59,360 --> 00:06:03,880
 about storage allocation on a bit by bit basis,

136
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:07,000
 we tend to need to know how to represent

137
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,760
 and print things out, not just in base 10.

138
00:06:09,760 --> 00:06:11,160
 And it really has to do with the fact

139
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:14,240
 that base eight and base 16 are better

140
00:06:14,240 --> 00:06:17,600
 at printing out binary data, raw data.

141
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:20,120
 10 is the number like where, you know,

142
00:06:20,120 --> 00:06:21,400
 how many pizzas do you want?

143
00:06:21,400 --> 00:06:23,960
 I want 16 pizzas or 22 pizzas.

144
00:06:23,960 --> 00:06:27,120
 It's our natural, the way we think, the way humans think.

145
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:28,840
 So talk about, to talk about bases,

146
00:06:28,840 --> 00:06:31,280
 let's start by just reviewing what base 10 means.

147
00:06:31,280 --> 00:06:33,640
 There is, you know, the ones place and the tens place

148
00:06:33,640 --> 00:06:35,440
 and of course later there's hundreds and thousands,

149
00:06:35,440 --> 00:06:40,440
 but the four in 42 represents four tens.

150
00:06:40,440 --> 00:06:44,400
 So you can think of it as four times 10, which is 40

151
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:47,080
 and then the ones place is two more.

152
00:06:47,080 --> 00:06:51,120
 So 42 is 40 plus two, which is kind of redundant.

153
00:06:51,120 --> 00:06:53,360
 We do that instinctively.

154
00:06:53,360 --> 00:06:55,600
 So now let's take a look at base eight.

155
00:06:55,600 --> 00:07:01,600
 So 42 in base 10 is 52 in base eight.

156
00:07:01,600 --> 00:07:03,080
 And what base eight is really doing

157
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:05,920
 is it means that the digits in the two places

158
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:07,560
 means something different,

159
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:10,920
 meaning the five and 52 represents an eight.

160
00:07:10,920 --> 00:07:14,660
 So there's five eights in this number

161
00:07:14,660 --> 00:07:16,640
 that we're dealing with and two ones.

162
00:07:16,640 --> 00:07:20,920
 And so five times eight is 40 and two times one is two.

163
00:07:20,920 --> 00:07:25,920
 And so converting from 52 base eight to 52 base 10,

164
00:07:25,920 --> 00:07:27,520
 we get to 42.

165
00:07:27,520 --> 00:07:29,440
 And we used base eight and again,

166
00:07:29,440 --> 00:07:31,720
 base eight lines up perfectly with base two

167
00:07:31,720 --> 00:07:36,120
 'cause three base two digits equals one base eight digit.

168
00:07:36,120 --> 00:07:39,200
 And I did a lot of base eight in the early days,

169
00:07:39,200 --> 00:07:41,920
 but base 16 is really the way we tend to do it now

170
00:07:41,920 --> 00:07:43,280
 'cause it's a little more dense.

171
00:07:43,280 --> 00:07:45,120
 The rightmost place is still the ones

172
00:07:45,120 --> 00:07:46,740
 and the next place is the 16s.

173
00:07:46,740 --> 00:07:51,440
 So the two in the 16s place represents two times 16 or 32.

174
00:07:51,440 --> 00:07:53,840
 And then what's left over is 10,

175
00:07:53,840 --> 00:07:58,840
 which we represent with an A and 10 plus 32 is 42.

176
00:07:58,920 --> 00:08:02,000
 Now the problem is, is we only have digits zero through nine.

177
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 So by convention, 10 is A, 11 is B, 12 is C,

178
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:10,880
 13 is D, 14 is E and 15 is F.

179
00:08:10,880 --> 00:08:13,540
 F is all the ones, it's four ones.

180
00:08:13,540 --> 00:08:16,020
 I know that, I just like four ones.

181
00:08:16,020 --> 00:08:20,260
 So I can convert hex from hex to base two,

182
00:08:20,260 --> 00:08:21,760
 like very, very quickly.

183
00:08:21,760 --> 00:08:25,380
 And if I need to look at a dump of some memory,

184
00:08:25,380 --> 00:08:27,760
 I can dump it in hex and then when I need to,

185
00:08:27,760 --> 00:08:30,560
 I can convert it to base two.

186
00:08:30,560 --> 00:08:32,460
 So just converting back and forth

187
00:08:32,460 --> 00:08:36,460
 between base 16 and base two is a bit of a trick.

188
00:08:36,460 --> 00:08:39,080
 And I don't really care if you do much of this,

189
00:08:39,080 --> 00:08:41,260
 you can grab this sample code and play with it.

190
00:08:41,260 --> 00:08:43,880
 This is a conversion from base 10,

191
00:08:43,880 --> 00:08:46,060
 a base number like one, two, three, four,

192
00:08:46,060 --> 00:08:48,220
 to base eight and then base 16.

193
00:08:48,220 --> 00:08:53,560
 And the way this one does it is it converts the number

194
00:08:53,560 --> 00:08:58,560
 in effect from the rightmost number up to the low digit

195
00:08:58,560 --> 00:09:01,440
 up to the high digit.

196
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:04,640
 And so what you do is you use the modulo function.

197
00:09:04,640 --> 00:09:06,740
 And so you take your number one, two, three, four,

198
00:09:06,740 --> 00:09:08,440
 and you take it modulo eight,

199
00:09:08,440 --> 00:09:11,560
 and what's left over as a remainder is two.

200
00:09:11,560 --> 00:09:14,400
 So that's the far right number in the new one.

201
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:17,440
 And then you chop it off with integer division,

202
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:22,620
 you chop that off and see what's left and that's 154.

203
00:09:22,620 --> 00:09:25,600
 And you're accumulating the two in the converted number.

204
00:09:25,600 --> 00:09:28,840
 And then you take the modulo of 154, modulo eight,

205
00:09:28,840 --> 00:09:32,520
 and you get two, and then you chop off the next eight

206
00:09:32,520 --> 00:09:36,120
 with integer divide by four and you get 19.

207
00:09:36,120 --> 00:09:38,840
 So now your bottom two digits are two, two.

208
00:09:38,840 --> 00:09:42,200
 And then you do 19 modulo eight and you get three.

209
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:44,840
 And that next digit from the right is a three.

210
00:09:44,840 --> 00:09:46,000
 Then you divide by eight,

211
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,280
 integer divide by eight to get what's left over.

212
00:09:48,280 --> 00:09:49,600
 And that's below eight.

213
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:53,560
 And so that the fourth digit from the right is a two.

214
00:09:53,560 --> 00:09:57,940
 So one, two, three, four in base eight is two, three, two, two.

215
00:09:57,940 --> 00:10:01,080
 And you can do the exact same thing.

216
00:10:01,080 --> 00:10:03,120
 The difference is you gotta look up the digits

217
00:10:03,120 --> 00:10:07,280
 because the base 16 needs the A, B, C, D, E, F.

218
00:10:07,280 --> 00:10:08,720
 And so I make a little string.

219
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:10,880
 Now we're talking Python here.

220
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:15,360
 And so we do repeatedly modulo 16, integer divide by 16,

221
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:19,420
 modulo 16, integer divide by 16, modulo 16,

222
00:10:19,420 --> 00:10:20,720
 integer divide by 16.

223
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:22,360
 And so we take one, two, three, four.

224
00:10:22,360 --> 00:10:24,620
 And when we convert it to base 16,

225
00:10:24,620 --> 00:10:28,560
 it kind of comes up from the bottom as two D four,

226
00:10:28,560 --> 00:10:30,120
 which we read four D two.

227
00:10:30,120 --> 00:10:32,800
 So that's just an algorithm that converts these.

228
00:10:32,800 --> 00:10:35,240
 You tend to use this modulo.

229
00:10:35,240 --> 00:10:38,680
 And that's how we can convert from one base to another.

230
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:40,720
 Now it's not critical in this class.

231
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:43,600
 We're not gonna spend a lot of time converting bases,

232
00:10:43,600 --> 00:10:46,200
 but we just need to be aware that

233
00:10:46,200 --> 00:10:51,200
 because there was so much awareness of how bits were stored,

234
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:53,620
 we tended to print a lot of stuff out

235
00:10:53,620 --> 00:10:55,560
 in hexadecimal or in base eight.

236
00:10:55,560 --> 00:10:59,340
 And so I just want you to know what those things are.

237
00:10:59,340 --> 00:11:00,440
 So if you look, for example,

238
00:11:00,440 --> 00:11:02,860
 at the ASCII chart that we've already seen,

239
00:11:02,860 --> 00:11:06,040
 you see that it shows us that the letter A is 65,

240
00:11:06,040 --> 00:11:10,120
 and in hex it's 41, and in octal it's 101,

241
00:11:10,120 --> 00:11:12,020
 and in base two, or binary,

242
00:11:12,020 --> 00:11:14,640
 it's one and a bunch of zeros and a one.

243
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:17,320
 And so this is just something that's making,

244
00:11:17,320 --> 00:11:20,640
 and in the old days you had to be just much more aware

245
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:23,480
 of the real bits inside the computer,

246
00:11:23,480 --> 00:11:26,560
 and hex and base eight, hex and octal,

247
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:29,600
 were better ways to sort of know what the bits were.

248
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:32,140
 So there you go.

249
00:11:32,140 --> 00:11:37,360
 Now another thing that C really was

250
00:11:37,360 --> 00:11:39,040
 one of the early innovative language

251
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:42,000
 was byte addressable computers, right?

252
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 And so we don't think much, everything's a string,

253
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,880
 and we can look at the characters in the string.

254
00:11:48,880 --> 00:11:52,080
 But in the old days, before C

255
00:11:52,080 --> 00:11:55,280
 and the generation of computers that kind of triggered C,

256
00:11:55,280 --> 00:11:58,780
 we didn't have characters.

257
00:11:58,780 --> 00:12:01,040
 You couldn't, in the hardware, load a character.

258
00:12:01,040 --> 00:12:02,460
 You could only load a word,

259
00:12:02,460 --> 00:12:05,060
 and then you had to find the character within the word.

260
00:12:05,060 --> 00:12:08,360
 And the language that really was the immediate precursor

261
00:12:08,360 --> 00:12:10,000
 to C was the B language.

262
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:13,900
 And the difference was is the B language was a really cool,

263
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:16,080
 low-level word-oriented language,

264
00:12:16,080 --> 00:12:17,880
 and then the C language came from B

265
00:12:17,880 --> 00:12:19,880
 and became a byte-oriented language.

266
00:12:19,880 --> 00:12:24,000
 And so C sort of like said, we're gonna do byte addressing.

267
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:29,000
 So if I take a look at the way I had to do character support

268
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:33,140
 in a CD6-6500, which is the computer I was using

269
00:12:33,140 --> 00:12:38,140
 in like 1975, 1976, it was a scientific computer.

270
00:12:38,960 --> 00:12:41,960
 It barely cared about printing characters.

271
00:12:41,960 --> 00:12:43,960
 It didn't even have lowercase.

272
00:12:43,960 --> 00:12:48,400
 It had 60-bit words and packed 6-bit uppercase characters

273
00:12:48,400 --> 00:12:52,360
 into those words, and it used a series of zeros

274
00:12:52,360 --> 00:12:53,200
 to fill it up.

275
00:12:53,200 --> 00:12:58,200
 And so if I put the words Hello World into the CDC6500,

276
00:12:58,200 --> 00:13:04,040
 it took two words, and Hello W-O-R-L

277
00:13:04,040 --> 00:13:07,460
 was packed into the first word, and D was in the second one,

278
00:13:07,460 --> 00:13:09,920
 and then we did what was called zero filling.

279
00:13:09,920 --> 00:13:12,600
 The rest of those characters were all zeros,

280
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:15,600
 the integer zero, zero, zero, zero, zero, zero, zero, zero.

281
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:19,000
 And if I wanted to know what the fifth character

282
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:24,080
 of this two-word string was, like the O, for example,

283
00:13:24,080 --> 00:13:26,360
 you would create a mask, and in that mask,

284
00:13:26,360 --> 00:13:30,100
 you would have zeros where you wanted to get rid of stuff

285
00:13:30,100 --> 00:13:31,780
 and ones where you wanted to copy stuff.

286
00:13:31,780 --> 00:13:34,260
 So you would take Hello World and you'd run it

287
00:13:34,260 --> 00:13:37,120
 through this mask with the bits in the right position,

288
00:13:37,120 --> 00:13:40,120
 and then you would get the O and all zeros

289
00:13:40,120 --> 00:13:43,280
 in the rest of the word, and then you would have to shift it

290
00:13:43,280 --> 00:13:45,640
 half the way down, 'cause there were 10 characters,

291
00:13:45,640 --> 00:13:49,320
 so you had to shift it five characters to the right,

292
00:13:49,320 --> 00:13:52,800
 and then you would have the letter O

293
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:55,240
 in the bottom six bits of that word,

294
00:13:55,240 --> 00:13:57,600
 and then I could write an if statement.

295
00:13:57,600 --> 00:14:00,080
 That's how I would say if the fifth character

296
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:03,780
 is the letter O, I had to extract the fifth character

297
00:14:03,780 --> 00:14:04,620
 by hand.

298
00:14:05,520 --> 00:14:08,480
 So you can imagine how happy I was

299
00:14:08,480 --> 00:14:10,240
 when I began to see programming languages

300
00:14:10,240 --> 00:14:12,760
 that allowed me to use more of an array syntax

301
00:14:12,760 --> 00:14:17,200
 and say strings of five, or even in this case,

302
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:19,160
 zero, one, two, three, four, strings of four,

303
00:14:19,160 --> 00:14:21,420
 where I could treat characters as an array.

304
00:14:21,420 --> 00:14:26,420
 The notion of a character array for me in 1977 was,

305
00:14:26,420 --> 00:14:29,760
 what, why would you, you know, you couldn't do that, right?

306
00:14:29,760 --> 00:14:33,280
 And so we, you know,

307
00:14:33,280 --> 00:14:38,000
 a whole generation of programmers went,

308
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:39,760
 go through their entire career

309
00:14:39,760 --> 00:14:42,200
 without having to do any masking and shifting.

310
00:14:42,200 --> 00:14:44,440
 So this chapter's gonna talk to you about it,

311
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:46,360
 and you might say, well, if C was so good

312
00:14:46,360 --> 00:14:50,260
 at doing it for you, why did they show it?

313
00:14:50,260 --> 00:14:51,680
 And that is that people like me

314
00:14:51,680 --> 00:14:54,400
 would not have had respect for this language

315
00:14:54,400 --> 00:14:55,880
 if it weren't for the fact that they had

316
00:14:55,880 --> 00:14:57,460
 a good masking and shifting,

317
00:14:57,460 --> 00:14:59,520
 'cause we were doing that all the time

318
00:14:59,520 --> 00:15:01,460
 in these word-oriented computers

319
00:15:01,460 --> 00:15:03,400
 and word-oriented languages.

320
00:15:03,400 --> 00:15:07,220
 And just as C and Unix were making

321
00:15:07,220 --> 00:15:08,800
 the world safe for characters,

322
00:15:08,800 --> 00:15:11,400
 then we had this other problem.

323
00:15:11,400 --> 00:15:13,760
 And I'm only gonna talk a little bit about this.

324
00:15:13,760 --> 00:15:17,000
 Just don't worry about it.

325
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:19,160
 The concept of indianess.

326
00:15:19,160 --> 00:15:23,660
 So if you're loading words,

327
00:15:23,660 --> 00:15:28,600
 do you load them with the least significant digits first,

328
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:31,360
 or the most significant digits first?

329
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:36,360
 And most computers were big-endian,

330
00:15:36,360 --> 00:15:40,920
 and big-endian to us software developers

331
00:15:40,920 --> 00:15:42,840
 made the most sense, 'cause that's how we thought

332
00:15:42,840 --> 00:15:43,840
 it would lay out.

333
00:15:43,840 --> 00:15:48,040
 But it turns out that a few processors wanted to load,

334
00:15:48,040 --> 00:15:49,040
 if they were gonna do an add,

335
00:15:49,040 --> 00:15:52,680
 they wanted to load the low end of the integer first

336
00:15:52,680 --> 00:15:53,880
 so they could start the addition

337
00:15:53,880 --> 00:15:55,440
 while they're bringing in the high end,

338
00:15:55,440 --> 00:15:59,320
 and they could overlap the load and the add.

339
00:15:59,320 --> 00:16:02,520
 And then Intel, which in those days

340
00:16:02,520 --> 00:16:03,920
 wasn't all that popular,

341
00:16:03,920 --> 00:16:06,000
 but they were so interested

342
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:07,840
 in the microprocessor performance

343
00:16:07,840 --> 00:16:09,240
 that they became little-endian

344
00:16:09,240 --> 00:16:11,960
 so that their loading and addition were fast.

345
00:16:11,960 --> 00:16:13,520
 And so we've been stuck with

346
00:16:13,520 --> 00:16:16,420
 a lot of little-endian microprocessors since then,

347
00:16:16,420 --> 00:16:18,460
 and big-endian and little-endian,

348
00:16:18,460 --> 00:16:21,640
 it's one of the harder things to solve, really.

349
00:16:21,640 --> 00:16:22,520
 It really is.

350
00:16:22,520 --> 00:16:24,500
 And so I'm gonna show you some code.

351
00:16:25,720 --> 00:16:29,400
 I really, all I want you to do

352
00:16:29,400 --> 00:16:31,160
 is feel sorry for those of us

353
00:16:31,160 --> 00:16:34,080
 who had to figure out little-endian and big-endian.

354
00:16:34,080 --> 00:16:35,640
 And let me just give you an outline

355
00:16:35,640 --> 00:16:37,140
 of what this code is doing.

356
00:16:37,140 --> 00:16:39,160
 I'm not gonna walk through it in detail.

357
00:16:39,160 --> 00:16:41,840
 It just is kinda scary.

358
00:16:41,840 --> 00:16:44,960
 So, and you're not even gonna understand

359
00:16:44,960 --> 00:16:47,360
 most of this code until chapter five.

360
00:16:47,360 --> 00:16:50,760
 It's just, let's just talk a little bit about the bits

361
00:16:50,760 --> 00:16:53,400
 and how masking and shifting would have worked

362
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:56,020
 if we didn't have character arrays.

363
00:16:56,020 --> 00:16:57,560
 So what I'm doing in this program

364
00:16:57,560 --> 00:16:59,920
 is I'm creating a character array.

365
00:16:59,920 --> 00:17:01,440
 The length of this character array

366
00:17:01,440 --> 00:17:04,560
 is hello world plus one for the terminator,

367
00:17:04,560 --> 00:17:08,040
 H-E-L-L-O space W-O-R-L-D.

368
00:17:08,040 --> 00:17:12,760
 So 11 plus one should be 12 characters are allocated.

369
00:17:12,760 --> 00:17:14,440
 And then what I'm doing in this next line

370
00:17:14,440 --> 00:17:17,520
 that says int star S-I

371
00:17:17,520 --> 00:17:20,400
 is I'm actually saying I wanna take the same storage

372
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:23,120
 and pretend it's an integer array.

373
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:25,440
 And so that's what that line is.

374
00:17:25,440 --> 00:17:29,000
 It takes the address of the beginning of the first character

375
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:32,720
 and convert it from a pointer to a character,

376
00:17:32,720 --> 00:17:35,200
 which is char S is a pointer to a character,

377
00:17:35,200 --> 00:17:37,000
 and have it be a pointer to an integer.

378
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:39,240
 And again, I'm sort of like jumping ahead in chapter five.

379
00:17:39,240 --> 00:17:41,400
 So I'm not expecting to understand all this.

380
00:17:41,400 --> 00:17:44,400
 I'm just making you aware of it.

381
00:17:44,400 --> 00:17:47,800
 So in those first two lines,

382
00:17:47,800 --> 00:17:52,800
 I've got a character array and an integer array.

383
00:17:53,360 --> 00:17:57,480
 Okay, and this is a 32-bit integer.

384
00:17:57,480 --> 00:18:02,240
 And so that means that the characters are stuck

385
00:18:02,240 --> 00:18:05,920
 into 32-bit integers in a little endian way.

386
00:18:05,920 --> 00:18:11,280
 And so if you look, that means that

387
00:18:11,280 --> 00:18:14,040
 if you just look at memory from left to right,

388
00:18:14,040 --> 00:18:19,040
 that the lowest of the first four, which is 32 bits,

389
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:24,880
 the first character that comes out is the L, right?

390
00:18:24,880 --> 00:18:27,040
 And you can see the little endian,

391
00:18:27,040 --> 00:18:29,840
 which in your mind thinks it should be shifted,

392
00:18:29,840 --> 00:18:32,320
 but that's because this is running on a little endian computer.

393
00:18:32,320 --> 00:18:34,760
 And different computers will give you different results.

394
00:18:34,760 --> 00:18:37,100
 And this is a little endian example.

395
00:18:37,100 --> 00:18:43,200
 And so you can see with masking and shifting

396
00:18:43,200 --> 00:18:47,440
 where I'm gonna try to get the E out,

397
00:18:47,440 --> 00:18:49,280
 which would normally be the second character,

398
00:18:49,280 --> 00:18:51,200
 but it's kind of the second from the bottom

399
00:18:51,200 --> 00:18:52,880
 of the first integer.

400
00:18:52,880 --> 00:18:54,800
 And so what I do is I make a mask

401
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:57,320
 and I'm gonna print this out.

402
00:18:57,320 --> 00:19:02,040
 I take FF, which is eight bits of ones,

403
00:19:02,040 --> 00:19:04,600
 and then I shift it up eight characters to the left.

404
00:19:04,600 --> 00:19:06,820
 And you can see that in the printout.

405
00:19:06,820 --> 00:19:11,720
 And then I mask out that character, which is the E,

406
00:19:11,720 --> 00:19:13,640
 but then it's in the wrong position.

407
00:19:13,640 --> 00:19:15,640
 And then I have to take that masked result

408
00:19:15,640 --> 00:19:17,960
 and I have to shift it back down eight

409
00:19:17,960 --> 00:19:19,920
 so that it's in the bottom part.

410
00:19:19,920 --> 00:19:22,840
 So now I can check to see what that letter is.

411
00:19:22,840 --> 00:19:25,560
 This is how I would pull out the second character

412
00:19:25,560 --> 00:19:29,160
 of a string so I could check to see if it's an E,

413
00:19:29,160 --> 00:19:30,640
 because I can't compare directly

414
00:19:30,640 --> 00:19:31,960
 the second character of string, right?

415
00:19:31,960 --> 00:19:34,360
 And Python, you're like, why are we doing this?

416
00:19:34,360 --> 00:19:37,520
 And that's why you build a string class

417
00:19:37,520 --> 00:19:39,800
 instead of use a character array for this.

418
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:42,680
 And I've made it even worse by starting

419
00:19:42,680 --> 00:19:45,000
 with taking a character array and viewing it

420
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:47,960
 as an integer array, and then playing with the integers.

421
00:19:47,960 --> 00:19:54,340
 So, you don't have to understand this.

422
00:19:54,340 --> 00:19:59,880
 Just be thankful that you use Python.

423
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:02,360
 And if you don't use Python, you use C.

424
00:20:02,360 --> 00:20:05,000
 And whether it's a big-endian or a little-endian machine,

425
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:07,160
 you can treat an array of characters

426
00:20:07,160 --> 00:20:10,120
 as an array of characters, and you can get the third one

427
00:20:10,120 --> 00:20:15,120
 or the fifth one with a square bracket notation, okay?

428
00:20:15,120 --> 00:20:20,280
 Storage allocation, storage allocation, storage allocation.

429
00:20:20,280 --> 00:20:22,720
 So a summary of this lecture is we talked

430
00:20:22,720 --> 00:20:24,160
 about number-based conversion.

431
00:20:24,160 --> 00:20:25,920
 We talked a little bit about division,

432
00:20:25,920 --> 00:20:28,700
 why the Python 2 integer division happened.

433
00:20:28,700 --> 00:20:31,320
 I don't really have a really good answer for that.

434
00:20:31,320 --> 00:20:33,520
 Concept of integers and words and bytes

435
00:20:33,520 --> 00:20:35,520
 and masking and shifting and characters.

436
00:20:35,520 --> 00:20:38,480
 Just because these topics are covered in this chapter,

437
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:41,840
 and they will feel very foreign to you and unnatural.

438
00:20:41,840 --> 00:20:44,360
 But just give 'em a shot, read through 'em,

439
00:20:44,360 --> 00:20:47,720
 understand them, and they'll make sense later.

440
00:20:47,720 --> 00:20:49,880
 Later, we're gonna learn about structures

441
00:20:49,880 --> 00:20:54,360
 and pointers and addresses advancing and stuff like that.

442
00:20:54,360 --> 00:20:57,240
 It'll all make a lot more sense coming up.

443
00:20:57,240 --> 00:20:59,820
 (gentle music)

